# Waste Management Gaps Analysis

## Scope
Hargeisa, Republic of Somaliland

## Key Gaps
- Lack of waste bins
- Absence of community waste tanks
- Poor waste segregation practices

## Root Causes
- Limited investment in waste management infrastructure
- Weak coordination between government authorities and private service providers
- Low level of public awareness on waste segregation and proper disposal
- Absence of structured monitoring and reporting systems

## Impact
- Environmental pollution
- Public health risks
- Inefficient waste collection

## Affected Areas
- High-density residential neighborhoods
- Markets and public spaces
- Areas near drainage systems and roadsides

## Analysis
The assessment indicates that waste management challenges in Hargeisa are primarily driven by infrastructure shortages and institutional coordination gaps. The absence of adequate waste bins and community tanks leads to uncontrolled waste disposal in open areas. Additionally, weak public awareness contributes to improper waste handling practices. These issues collectively result in environmental degradation and increased health risks.

## Recommendations
- Install sufficient household-level waste bins
- Establish community-level waste tanks in strategic locations
- Implement public awareness campaigns on waste segregation
- Strengthen coordination between public institutions and private companies
- Introduce regular monitoring and reporting mechanisms
